---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HauntedCursor from "../../components/HauntedCursor.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <!-- VT323 Retro Font -->
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=VT323&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">

  <div class="min-h-screen bg-secondary px-4 sm:px-8 py-8 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      <article class="prose prose-invert max-w-none">
        <div data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="1000">
          <h1 class="tv-title tv-title-vhs">
            <span class="on-air">ON AIR</span> RECIPE GUIDE
          </h1>
          
          <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/60 mb-8 sm:mb-12 italic border-l-4 border-primary/30 pl-4 py-2">
            I wrote this guide for my cousin back in 2021 when they were just starting to cook on their own. 
            Looking back at it now, I'm surprised by how much of this I still use today‚Äîthese recipes and 
            tricks still are my go-tos.
            <span class="block mt-2 text-primary/80">‚Äî Todd, 2025</span>
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-16">
            <!-- Recipes Section -->
            <section>
              <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-primary mb-8 flex items-center gap-3">
                <span class="text-3xl">üìú</span>
                Recipes
              </h2>

              <!-- Broccoli Beef -->
              <div class="mb-12 bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-6 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                <h3 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                  Broccoli Beef / Corn Starch Slurry Sauced Veggies
                </h3>
                <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  This classic Chinese dish is a "healthy" Panda Express staple! The secret is in the cornstarch 
                  slurry sauce. It only takes a few ingredients and is relatively easy/quick to cook!
                </p>
                
                <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mb-4">
                  <strong class="text-primary">Recipe:</strong> 
                  <a href="https://www.justataste.com/easy-beef-and-broccoli-recipe/" 
                     target="_blank" 
                     rel="noopener noreferrer"
                     class="text-primary/60 hover:text-primary underline transition-colors">
                    Just a Taste - Easy Beef and Broccoli
                  </a>
                </p>

                <div class="space-y-4 text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80">
                  <p class="italic text-primary/70">
                    This is a great recipe to follow ^^ below I listed some substitutes for some of the ingredients!
                  </p>

                  <div class="space-y-3 pl-4 border-l-2 border-primary/20">
                    <div>
                      <strong class="text-primary">Brown sugar:</strong> honey or white sugar work fine!
                      <p class="text-sm text-primary/60 mt-1 italic">
                        You'll notice that sugar is a huge aspect of soy sauce-based sauces - it brings out the 
                        delicious teriyaki-like flavors of soy sauce.
                      </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                      <strong class="text-primary">White onion:</strong> whites of green onion, shallots, just garlic, none
                      <p class="text-sm text-primary/60 mt-1 italic">
                        This is definitely optional but can add a lot of flavors -- I think that garlic is necessary 
                        but onion is a plus if you have it!
                      </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                      <strong class="text-primary">Broccoli florets:</strong> regular broccoli, bok choi, bell pepper/onion mix, mushrooms
                      <p class="text-sm text-primary/60 mt-1 italic">
                        This recipe is SUPER diverse -- you can pretty much substitute broccoli with anything and it 
                        will still come out delicious and saucy.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-primary/10 rounded p-4 space-y-2">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-primary">üí° Tips:</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-primary/70">
                      <li>Taste the sauce as you make it! It should be yummy and not overly salty.</li>
                      <li>Don't taste it until cooked when you add the cornstarch slurry.</li>
                      <li>Cornstarch dissolves better in cold water.</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-yellow-500/10 border border-yellow-500/30 rounded p-4">
                    <p class="font-bold text-yellow-300 mb-2">üåü STAR TIP:</p>
                    <p class="text-primary/80 mb-2">
                      Ever wonder why Chinese stir fried beef/pork is so soft? They tenderize it by soaking it in 
                      baking soda. Find out more about the science and how to do it:
                    </p>
                    <a href="https://www.cooksillustrated.com/how_tos/6707-tenderizing-meat-with-a-baking-soda-solution" 
                       target="_blank" 
                       rel="noopener noreferrer"
                       class="text-yellow-300/80 hover:text-yellow-300 underline text-sm transition-colors break-all">
                      Cook's Illustrated - Tenderizing Meat with Baking Soda
                    </a>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Slow Baked Salmon -->
              <div class="mb-12 bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-6 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                <h3 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                  Slow Baked Salmon
                </h3>
                <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  Literally, my favorite way to make salmon + it's a set and go do something else for a 15ish minute 
                  dish -- super easy to meal prep and super delicious!!
                </p>
                
                <div class="space-y-3 mb-4">
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/70">
                    <strong class="text-primary">Recipe:</strong> 
                    <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/slow-baked-salmon-with-lemon-and-thyme-365151" 
                       target="_blank" 
                       rel="noopener noreferrer"
                       class="text-primary/60 hover:text-primary underline transition-colors">
                      Epicurious - Slow-Baked Salmon
                    </a>
                  </p>
                  
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/70">
                    <strong class="text-primary">Favorite Marinade:</strong> 
                    <a href="https://www.bonappetit.com/recipe/crispy-skin-salmon-with-miso-honey-sauce" 
                       target="_blank" 
                       rel="noopener noreferrer"
                       class="text-primary/60 hover:text-primary underline transition-colors">
                      Bon App√©tit - Miso Honey Salmon
                    </a>
                  </p>
                </div>

                <div class="space-y-4 text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80">
                  <p class="italic text-primary/70">
                    I would follow the Epicurious recipe's cooking instructions but the marinating and seasoning 
                    process is completely up to you! Don't worry about the random herbs they have in this one and 
                    feel free to experiment with other salmon recipe seasoning/use what is in your pantry!
                  </p>

                  <p class="text-primary/80">
                    One of my favorite salmon recipes is the miso honey salmon by Bon App√©tit. I just take the 
                    sauce and coat the salmon with it/let it marinate in it for a bit then toss it in the oven!!
                  </p>

                  <p class="text-primary/70 italic">
                    Since it's such a low temperature - the salmon is not likely to burn (even if there are a lot 
                    of sugars in the sauce)
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-primary/10 rounded p-4">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">üçΩÔ∏è Personal Tip:</p>
                    <p class="text-primary/70">
                      I honestly like to take my salmon out at the 15-minute mark or if I'm away from the kitchen - 
                      I'll turn down the heat to 240-250¬∞F and let it go for 20 minutes. This is up to preference 
                      though because I like my salmon a bit undercooked.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Chicken or Beef Stew -->
              <div class="mb-12 bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-6 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                <h3 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                  Chicken or Beef Stew
                </h3>
                <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  Mastering the stew process is quick and honestly one of the most forgiving recipes (as long as 
                  you don't oversalt). Do you want to prepare something hearty during the winter months? Follow 
                  these recipes and you could have a few days of yummy stew!
                </p>
                
                <div class="space-y-2 mb-4">
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/70">
                    <strong class="text-primary">Bo Kho Recipe:</strong> 
                    <a href="https://thewoksoflife.com/bo-kho-spicy-vietnamese-beef-stew/" 
                       target="_blank" 
                       rel="noopener noreferrer"
                       class="text-primary/60 hover:text-primary underline transition-colors">
                      The Woks of Life - Spicy Vietnamese Beef Stew
                    </a>
                  </p>
                  
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/70">
                    <strong class="text-primary">Chicken Stew Recipe:</strong> 
                    <a href="https://www.slb.sg/recipe/miso-chicken-stew/" 
                       target="_blank" 
                       rel="noopener noreferrer"
                       class="text-primary/60 hover:text-primary underline transition-colors">
                      SLB - Miso Chicken Stew
                    </a>
                  </p>
                </div>

                <div class="space-y-4 text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80">
                  <p class="italic text-primary/70 mb-4">
                    These are examples of recipes that could be super yummy! Below, I'm going to list some factors 
                    that create a good stew:
                  </p>

                  <div class="space-y-4">
                    <div class="bg-primary/10 rounded p-4">
                      <p class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">ü•© The Right Pieces of Meat</p>
                      <p class="text-primary/70 mb-2">
                        Choose cuts that can take a long/slow cook -- this includes sirloin, brisket, and chicken 
                        thighs (the holy grail of overcooked meat). These meats are begging to be cooked for a 
                        slow and long time! They will stay soft and taste delicious when overcooked.
                      </p>
                      <p class="text-red-400/80 italic text-sm">
                        ‚ö†Ô∏è Never slow cook chicken breast - it's a crime.
                      </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="bg-primary/10 rounded p-4">
                      <p class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">üç∂ The Right Sauces + Stocks</p>
                      <p class="text-primary/70 mb-2">
                        For a general sauce mix - I'll use red wine to deglaze, soy sauce, honey, and some sort 
                        of acid (vinegar, lime, etc.) -- then to make the soup itself, water or chicken stock.
                      </p>
                      <p class="text-yellow-300 font-semibold text-sm">
                        When thinking about a sauce for anything, even stews, think about these three things: 
                        SALTY, SWEET, SOUR.
                      </p>
                      <p class="text-primary/60 text-sm mt-1 italic">
                        If your soup doesn't taste right add one of the following that may be missing.
                      </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="bg-primary/10 rounded p-4">
                      <p class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">üî• Searing Your Meats First</p>
                      <p class="text-primary/70 mb-2">
                        When searing anything in some oil - it flavors the oil and also creates this thing at the 
                        bottom of the pan called a <strong>fond</strong> -- fond cooking is a French technique 
                        that pretty much is deglazing whatever develops at the bottom of the pan (the yummy brown 
                        stuff that sticks to the bottom of the pan).
                      </p>
                      <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-primary/70 text-sm">
                        <li>Flavors the oil</li>
                        <li>Creates a fond that can be deglazed and further flavor your soup!</li>
                        <li>When deglazing - use a wooden spatula or spoon to scrape the fond and melt it into the liquid</li>
                        <li>Adds a brown color to your meat, making it look yummy :))</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-yellow-500/10 border border-yellow-500/30 rounded p-4 mt-4">
                    <p class="font-bold text-yellow-300 mb-2">üí° TIP:</p>
                    <p class="text-primary/80">
                      Recipes like Bo Kho may seem complicated but just try to use the most vital flavors/don't 
                      worry about getting all the ingredients - then substitute with whatever is in your pantry. 
                      IMO - the most vital parts of Bo Kho are <strong class="text-primary">star anise, fish sauce, 
                      tomato paste</strong> -- everything else not as necessary.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Asian Cucumber Salad -->
              <div class="mb-12 bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-6 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                <h3 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                  Asian Cucumber Salad
                </h3>
                <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  My go-to salad when I'm feeling lazy. It's super yummy and takes ten minutes to prepare! The 
                  sauce is simply rice vinegar, soy sauce, some sort of sugar -- hitting those three notes of a 
                  key sauce - <strong>SALTY. SWEET. SOUR.</strong>
                </p>
                
                <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mb-4">
                  <strong class="text-primary">Recipe:</strong> 
                  <a href="https://www.wellplated.com/asian-cucumber-salad/" 
                     target="_blank" 
                     rel="noopener noreferrer"
                     class="text-primary/60 hover:text-primary underline transition-colors">
                    Well Plated - Asian Cucumber Salad
                  </a>
                </p>

                <div class="space-y-3 text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80">
                  <p class="text-primary/70 italic">
                    Have fun with this one - cut it randomly for fun variable shapes to eat LOL.
                  </p>
                  <p class="text-primary/70 italic">
                    This one tastes better overtime!
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-yellow-500/10 border border-yellow-500/30 rounded p-4">
                    <p class="font-bold text-yellow-300 mb-2">üåü STAR TIP:</p>
                    <p class="text-primary/80">
                      Salads generally follow the <strong>SOUR</strong> aspect of good sauces the most.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Grocery Store Tips Section -->
            <section>
              <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-primary mb-8 flex items-center gap-3">
                <span class="text-3xl">üõçÔ∏è</span>
                Grocery Store / Random Tips
              </h2>

              <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
                <!-- Costco Fish Fillets -->
                <div class="bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-5 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                  <h3 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                    Costco Fish Fillets
                  </h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/80 leading-relaxed mb-3">
                    This is a hidden meal prep secret that will soon be revealed. Costco has these awesome, frozen, 
                    deboned fish packets in the frozen section. Usually near burger meat or shrimp. They're pretty 
                    affordable and is super easy to take out the night before to cook with the next day. I really 
                    like the branzino and the salmon.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-yellow-500/10 border border-yellow-500/30 rounded p-3">
                    <p class="text-yellow-300 text-sm">
                      üåü They have a lot of different versions! Make sure to find the ones that are deboned and 
                      have no scales!
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Breakfast Shin Noodle -->
                <div class="bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-5 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                  <h3 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                    The Breakfast Shin Noodle
                  </h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/80 leading-relaxed">
                    In college, I always had bacon and eggs for one-dish breakfast shin. I'd cut up a single slice 
                    of bacon into a pan, let it sear a little bit - then add water or leftover soup. Put in the 
                    shin, follow pack instructions with a tad bit of sugar ‚Üí egg ‚Üí cook for a bit ‚Üí top with green 
                    onion and eat in the pot.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Costco Beef Mandu -->
                <div class="bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-5 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                  <h3 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                    Costco Beef Mandu
                  </h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/80 leading-relaxed">
                    Yo - I'm in love with these beef mandus. They're quick, easy, and versatile. I pan fry them, 
                    I boil them, I toss them in soups, and sometimes I eat them with a random array of foods. 
                    They're honestly one of my favorite frozen dumplings and are super delicious/quick to cook.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Trader Joe's Salad -->
                <div class="bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-5 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                  <h3 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                    Trader Joe's Chopped Chicken Salad Kit
                  </h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/80 leading-relaxed">
                    This is the best salad kit I've ever had in my life. Period. It's sold at all Trader Joe's 
                    and one pack is about $4-5 for two to three servings of chicken salad - that can ultimately 
                    be meal prepped. Honestly, if you're extra hungry - this could be a full meal on its own.
                  </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Costco Shrimp Cocktails -->
                <div class="bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-5 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                  <h3 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                    Costco Shrimp Cocktails
                  </h3>
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/80 leading-relaxed mb-2 uppercase font-semibold text-primary">
                    DO NOT UNDERESTIMATE THIS SIMPLE BUT DELICIOUS COSTCO STAPLE.
                  </p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-primary/80 leading-relaxed">
                    For my entire childhood - I overlooked this and always thought, "it's just plain boiled shrimp." 
                    I was so wrong. I am convinced that this is one of the best meal items at Costco. It's simple, 
                    tangy, just the right chew, and an excellent snack/quick meal with some other thing. I always 
                    get this on a Costco run.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- General Grocery Beef Cuts -->
              <div class="mt-8 bg-primary/5 rounded-lg p-6 border border-primary/10 hover:border-primary/30 transition-all duration-300">
                <h3 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">
                  General Grocery (G.G.) Store Beef Cuts
                </h3>
                <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-primary/80 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
                  I'm going to start doing G.G. listings which stand for <strong>General Grocery</strong> -- these 
                  will be items that should be easy to find in all grocery stores! The first set of items to discuss 
                  for G.G. are beef cuts! Especially in American grocery stores - you may notice that beef is put 
                  on sale much more often there than Asian supermarkets. Always look for on sale beef cuts when you 
                  visit a general, American, grocery store!!!
                </p>

                <div class="space-y-6">
                  <div>
                    <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-green-400 mb-3">‚úÖ Types of Meats to Look Out For:</h4>
                    <div class="space-y-3 pl-4 border-l-2 border-green-400/30">
                      <div>
                        <strong class="text-primary">Rib/Ribeye pieces:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mt-1">
                          Anything ribeye is SOFT af -- it's pretty much the centerpiece of a rib so it's the 
                          muscle that moves the least. There are two-three types of ribeye pieces but they are 
                          all soft.
                        </p>
                      </div>

                      <div>
                        <strong class="text-primary">Flank/Skirt Steak:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mt-1">
                          BOMBB - thin and often on sale - it's always yummy. I especially love skirt steak nights. 
                          Marinade it in a semi acidic sauce and BOOM -- soft steak. Love using this in pretty much 
                          everything, except for soups.
                        </p>
                      </div>

                      <div>
                        <strong class="text-primary">Sirloin:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mt-1">
                          Sirloin is like the lean, but not as chewy cousin of Chuck. It is definitely a decent 
                          steak option, stewed meat, and also sliced meat -- generally cheaper than ribeye and 
                          easy to cut.
                        </p>
                      </div>

                      <div>
                        <strong class="text-primary">Tenderloin:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mt-1">
                          You know those cute small steaks - this is it. Roasted tenderloin is a super yummy date 
                          night meal and pretty easy to cook! However, some pieces are chewy so I advise trying 
                          to buy fatty pieces!
                        </p>
                      </div>

                      <div>
                        <strong class="text-primary">Brisket:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mt-1">
                          I love stewing up brisket. It's a fat chunk of meat and will last FOREVER. A slow cooked 
                          brisket is a yummy one.
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div>
                    <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-400 mb-3">‚ùå Types of Meats to Avoid:</h4>
                    <div class="pl-4 border-l-2 border-red-400/30">
                      <div>
                        <strong class="text-primary">Chuck:</strong>
                        <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 mt-1">
                          This is only good if you're slicing the meat thin or putting it through a tenderizing 
                          process or stew or cheap hotpot. Chuck is extremely tough (it's the muscle right below 
                          the neck of a cow) and can be hard to eat. I never suggest buying chuck steak.
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-primary/10 rounded p-4">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-primary mb-2">üìö HISTORY:</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-primary/70 leading-relaxed">
                      The price difference is a cultural difference - Americans eat beef everyday, all the time, 
                      having it go on sale is valuable because stores know that they will sell! + American beef 
                      is always valued. Asians eat beef on a special basis - it wasn't a protein that was often 
                      eaten back then, which is why beef is generally priced higher at Asian supermarkets.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </section>
          </div>

          <a 
            href="/blog/the-attic" 
            class="inline-block mt-12 text-primary/60 hover:text-white transition-colors duration-300"
          >
            ‚Üê Back to Attic
          </a>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <style>
    /* TV Title - VHS Style */
    .tv-title {
      font-family: 'VT323', 'Courier New', monospace;
      font-size: 2.2rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.15em;
      color: rgb(var(--color-primary) / 0.85);
      text-shadow: 
        0 0 8px rgb(var(--color-primary) / 0.3),
        0 0 16px rgb(var(--color-primary) / 0.15);
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 1rem;
    }

    .tv-title-vhs {
      animation: vhsWobble 4s ease-in-out infinite;
    }

    .on-air {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: #ff3333;
      animation: onAirPulse 1.5s ease-in-out infinite;
      padding: 0.25rem 0.6rem;
      background: rgba(255, 50, 50, 0.15);
      border: 1px solid #ff3333;
      border-radius: 3px;
      text-shadow: 0 0 8px #ff3333;
    }

    @keyframes onAirPulse {
      0%, 100% { opacity: 1; box-shadow: 0 0 8px #ff3333; }
      50% { opacity: 0.7; box-shadow: 0 0 4px #ff3333; }
    }

    @keyframes vhsWobble {
      0%, 100% { transform: translateX(0); }
      25% { transform: translateX(1px); }
      75% { transform: translateX(-1px); }
    }

    /* Override global VT323 for recipe content - use readable font */
    .min-h-screen p,
    .min-h-screen li,
    .min-h-screen span {
      font-family: 'Inter', system-ui, -apple-system, sans-serif !important;
      font-size: 1rem !important;
      letter-spacing: normal !important;
      line-height: 1.7 !important;
    }

    .min-h-screen .prose p,
    .min-h-screen .prose li {
      font-size: 1.05rem !important;
      line-height: 1.75 !important;
    }

    /* Keep VT323 for section headings */
    .min-h-screen h2,
    .min-h-screen h3 {
      font-family: 'VT323', 'Courier New', monospace !important;
      letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    }

    .min-h-screen h2 {
      font-size: 1.75rem !important;
    }

    .min-h-screen h3 {
      font-size: 1.35rem !important;
    }

    /* Tighter spacing for recipe cards */
    .space-y-16 {
      gap: 3rem;
    }

    .mb-12 {
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
    }

    /* Smaller tips boxes */
    .min-h-screen .bg-primary\/10,
    .min-h-screen .bg-yellow-500\/10 {
